Rabies - Zambia: RFI 971220000629
Date: Sat, 20 Dec 1997 09:15:42 EST
From: Shehzad Parvis <Ssparviz@aol.com>

That was a very critical question you asked about rabies post-exposure
prophylaxis as immunoglobulins are required according to WHO guidelines of
rabies post-exposure prophylaxis in any single or multiple transdermal
rabies prone wound and have to be instilled in the wound.
There are two issues concerning rabies immunoglobulins: affordability and
availability.
99% of post-exposure treatments which occur in developing countries would
not contain immunoglobulins. I can mention only about my experiences in
Pakistan. The two types human derived and equine derived with an immense
cost difference:
Cost in US $ (days of work by clerk)
Human Rabies immunoglobulin(HRIG) 5 ml=2000 I.U (20 IU/kg) 293 (100)
Equine rabies immunoglobulin (ERIG) 10 ml=2000 I.U (40 IU/Kg) 35 (12)
The cost of ERIG is 8-10 times less than HRIG. For a 50 kg person ERIG would
cost him Pak Rs.1,256 as compared to Human Rabies immunogloblin would cost
around Pak Rs.18,747.
I feel the problems here are 1. HRIG is too expensive as dog bites afflict
the indigent population. 2. Physicians don't know much about the importance
and safety of ERIG.
Immunoglobulins would be available in big cities at their suppliers store or
at tertiary care private hospitals here. This would usually be HRIG because
physicians fear anaphylaxis due to ERIG. This fear is unjustified especially
of the new products (Rabies antiserum produced by Pasteur Merieux Connaught,
France and Swiss & Serum Institute, Berne, Switzerland) which are safe. The
chances of anaphylaxis is 1 in 40,000 and even then its preventable shown in
studies published 10 years ago in Thailand.
There are also economic disincentives and animal right activism against ERIG
production in the West. Countries like Thailand and China in Asia are
producing their own ERIG to some extent. Hence production of safe equine
immunoglobulin needs to be increased in Third World Countries and its use
has to promoted among physicians. You would find numerous publications on
Rabies Immunoglobulins coming from Thailand by Dr. Henry Wilde at Queen
Saovobha Memmorial Institute, Bangkok.
The vaccine and regimen is being used in Zambia is important. Are the wounds
being cleaned promptly and thoroughly by soap and water? Dried and applied
with tincture of iodine or 60-80% ethanol? These steps might be life saving
as they may decrease the viral inoculum and kill the virus and might be
neglected by victims, primary care providers and physicians themselves.
--
Shehzad Parviz MD,
health professional,
ex-research officer,
Rabies worker
Community Heath Sciences Department,
The Aga Khan University,
Karachi, Pakistan.

