[3

Date: Sun, 21 Dec 1997 08:03:25 +0700 (BKK)
From: Henry Wilde <fmedhwl@chulkn.car.chula.ac.th>

WHO reports that over 90% of subjects exposed to rabies and given some form
of post exposure vaccine therapy do not receive RIG (WHO/Rabies 94.210,
Geneva). In Southeast and South Asia this is also the case except for
Thailand where the National Blood Center of the Thai Red Cross manufactures
HRIG and some ERIG is also being made locally as well as imported.
Human RIG (HRIG) is simply not affordable if purchased from abroad. It
Thailand it costs the equivalent of 100 days of labor for an low level civil
servant. In the other Asian countries it is even worse.
The new Equine RIG made in Europe and in small amounts in Thailand is
highly purified and carries a 1-1.5% serum sickness rate and only 1:40,000
cases had anaphylaxis. There is not enough of it worldwide (see: Wilde, H ,
Ann Int Med 1996;125: 233-236).
How effective is rabies vaccine alone in a true exposure? We do not know
exactly as it depends on many factors such as viral inoculum, where (near
nerve endings) etc. We do know, however, that vaccination even with the new
tissue culture vaccines will not give a "protective" AB response before day
10-14. We have seen deaths here in less time.
Our group also feels that the RIG is only effective if injected into the
bite sites. Given IM elsewhere does not result in much more than a barely
detectable systemic antibody response. Recent studies by J. Lang, A
Subcharoen and E. Miranda (In print) have worked out the kinetics of RIG
administration and confirm our long held impression that this is so.
Manufacturers of ERIG have closed down plants partly due to the low
profitability of this product used mostly in poor countries and also due to
pressure from animal rights groups who do not like horses to be used as
blood donors. If you wish to know more, read the WHO document and paper in
Annals referenced above.
--
Henry Wilde, MD
Profesor of Medicine
Queen Saovabha Memorial Institute
Bangkok, Thailand

[4
Date: Mon, 22 Dec 1997 15:19:49 -0500
From: Steven_Wiersma@dcf.state.fl.us

I recently spent 4 years in Zambia and Eritrea. While I don't know about
RIG availability in Zambia, I found it unavailable in Eritrea. When my wife
was trying to provide PEP to several individuals who had been bitten by a
rabid dog, we could only find it at the US Embassy. No local sources for
RIG were found but fortunately the US Embassy allowed their supply to be
used and replaced as an emergency measure.
--
Steven Wiersma, MD, MPH
Deputy State Epidemiologist
Florida Department of Health
